On Wednesday Whelan, now 77, appeared every bit as out of touch when it came to the issue of his new manager and an exchange of racist, sexist and homophobic text messages and emails that remain the subject of an ongoing Football Association investigation.

As out of touch as the LMA when they dismissed Mackay’s exchanges with Iain Moody as ‘banter’, only to then apologise for the original apology.

Whelan said Mackay had been ‘unlucky’ and had ‘done a little bit wrong’, adding that the football club had endured ‘these little problems’ in the past before finally declaring the FA investigation would probably come to nothing.

Every bit as offensive and patronising was his dismissal of Lisa Nandy, the Wigan MP who wrote to Whelan last week echoing her constituents in expressing concern about Mackay’s possible appointment. ‘She’s not a Wigan girl by the way, she was imported into Wigan from another area, she’s not a Wigan lass, so she doesn’t understand football,’ he declared.

The truth is, no club should have even considered appointing Mackay while he remains the subject of such a serious investigation; one that remains two or three weeks away from completion.

