While Whelan says there is a clause in Mackay’s new contract that gives the club the right to take action should he now be charged, he already seems to think no action will be taken.

Whelan is being as disingenuous as the man who continues to insist he has already apologised for those text messages and emails.

During that apology in a staged interview with Sky, Mackay said he was responsible for only three offensive text messages or emails.

But he did so knowing full well there were more - and the following morning those messages were published on the pages of the Daily Mail.

One of them referred to Vincent Tan, his Malaysian former employer at Cardiff, as ‘a chink’.

